+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| New Copyright Alliance Formed In D.C.                              |
|   from the they-own-j00 dept.                                      |
|   posted by Zonk on Friday May 25, @09:42 (The Almighty Buck)      |
|   http://yro.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/25/1255202          |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]jombeewoof alerted us to a story that went past unnoticed last
weekend. A new [1]industry-backed 'Copyright Alliance' was formed in the
city of Washington, DC. Tasked with the nebulous goal of 'promoting the
value of copyright as an agent for creativity, jobs, and growth', the
ultimate goal of the organization is to strengthen copyright laws
overall. "Backed by organizations like the MPAA, NBC, News Corp., Disney,
Time Warner, the Business Software Alliance, Microsoft, ASCAP, the NBA,
and others, the Copyright Alliance has already secured initial support
from several members of Congress ... The group is headed by Patrick Ross,
a former senior fellow at the Progress & Freedom Foundation, a strongly
free-market think tank. Ross has written about IP issues for years, and
in a 2005 opinion piece claimed that he was 'looking for anyone who wants
to join me in seeking that elusive middle ground.' His new gig may be a
strange place to fight for that 'middle ground' in any meaningful sense,
as the Alliance is dedicated to 'strengthening copyright law' using
'bilateral, regional, and multilateral agreements to protect creators'
and advancing educational programs 'that teach the value of strong
copyright.'"

Discuss this story at:
    http://yro.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/05/25/1255202

Links:
    0. http://www.myspace.com/jombeewoof
    1. http://arstechnica.com/news.ars/post/20070518-new-copyright-alliance-hopes-to-strengthen-copyright-law.html


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Sony Sued for Blu-Ray Patent Violation                             |
|   from the how-shiny-is-too-shiny dept.                            |
|   posted by Zonk on Friday May 25, @10:23 (Sony)                   |
|   http://yro.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/25/1344249          |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

Jaidan writes "According to a Gamespot article, a California-based
company named Target Technology is [0]suing Sony over patents it
allegedly holds for silver based reflective surfaces. The suit claims
that products marketed under the Blu-ray name infringe on a patent it
owns for reflective layer materials in optical discs. Target is seeking a
permanent injunction preventing Sony from violating its patent rights in
the future, as well as damages with interest, multiplied due to what it
characterizes as deliberate and willful infringement. ' The patent
addresses what Target called a need for specific types of silver-based
alloys with the advantages (but not the price) of gold. According to the
patent, the alloys are also more resistant to corrosion than pure silver.
Target does not specify in its suit whether it believes all of Sony's
Blu-ray discs infringe on its patent, or the suit applies to just a
portion of the discs manufactured. The patent was filed in April of 2004
and granted in March of 2006.'"

Discuss this story at:
    http://yro.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/05/25/1344249

Links:
    0. http://www.gamespot.com/news/6171498.html?om_act=convert&om_clk=newstop&tag=newstop;title;2


