| Dell PCs with Ubuntu Are A Little Less Expensive                   |
|   from the penguin-pass dept.                                      |
|   posted by Zonk on Friday May 25, @12:25 (Linux Business)         |
|   http://linux.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/25/1529201        |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]Chandon Seldon writes "Contrary to many [1]earlier reports, it turns
out that Dell's prices for its Ubuntu PCs [2]are cheaper than similar
Windows Vista PCs for all three Models. Ars Technica reports: 'So it
turns out that not including Windows saves the consumer $50 from the
regular list price. This amount is not too far off from what a large OEM
like Dell would pay for a volume discount for Windows Vista Home Basic
(the regular OEM price is about $95). Many value PC sellers try to make
up for the cost of a Windows license by bundling demo and trial versions
of software such as AOL (affectionately known as "crapware"), for which
they receive money from software companies looking to increase their
distribution levels. Dell is no exception to this practice, although on
their web site it allows customers to select the option of not including
various applications.' For direct comparisons, Nat Tuck of Umass-Lowell
has put together [3]a simple page showing prices for Ubuntu and
Windows-based PCs."

Discuss this story at:
    http://linux.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/05/25/1529201

