+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| CSS of DVDs Ruled 'Ineffective' by Finnish Courts                  |
|   from the rip-away-my-pretties-rip-away dept.                     |
|   posted by Zonk on Friday May 25, @14:26 (Media)                  |
|   http://yro.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/25/1653209          |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

An anonymous reader writes "The CSS protection used in DVDs has been
[0]ruled "ineffective" by Helsinki District Court. This means that CSS is
not covered by the Finnish copyright law amendment of 2005 (based on
[1]EU Copyright Directive from 2001), allowing it to be freely
circumvented. Quoting the press release: ' The conclusions of the court
can be applied all over Europe since the word effective comes directly
from the directive ... A protection measure is no longer effective, when
there is widely available end-user software implementing a circumvention
method. My understanding is that this is not technology-dependent. The
decision can therefore be applied to Blu-Ray and HD-DVD as well in the
future.'"

Discuss this story at:
    http://yro.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/05/25/1653209

Links:
    0. http://www.turre.com/blog/?p=102
    1. http://europa.eu.int/eur-lex/pri/en/oj/dat/2001/l_167/l_16720010622en00100019.pdf


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Best Buy Accused of Overcharging                                   |
|   from the maybe-shouldn't-be-quite-so-greedy dept.                |
|   posted by Zonk on Friday May 25, @15:11 (Businesses)             |
|   http://slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/25/1855233              |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

An anonymous reader writes "Connecticut's Attorney General Richard
Blumenthal has [0]accused Best Buy of overcharging its customers. His
accusation is that customers see one price on Best Buy's website, in
stores salespeople would show them a different internal site from a
kiosk. Best Buy denies the charges. 'Previously, the company confirmed
that store employees have access to an internal Web site that looks
nearly identical to the public BestBuy.com site, but the company's policy
is always to offer customers the lowest quoted price unless it's
specifically identified as a deal available only to online shoppers.
Jerry Farrell Jr., Connecticut's consumer protection commissioner, said
the lawsuit should be a warning to companies to be more transparent in
their business practices.'"

Discuss this story at:
    http://slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/05/25/1855233

Links:
    0. http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/05/24/AR2007052401258.html


